Japan Stock Futures Rise on U.S. Data; Australia Little Changed

-- B y   Y o s h i a k i   N o h a r a   a n d   S a t o s h i   K a w a n o
-- 
2011-08-22T23:22:38Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-22/japanese-stock-futures-rise-on-u-s-production-australia-little-changed.html
Japanese  stock futures  rose after
data showing a pickup in U.S. industrial production helped keep
the world’s largest economy from weakening further and as
prospects for an end to the war in Libya boosted European
shares. Australian stock futures were little changed.  American depositary receipts of Honda Motor Co., a Japanese
carmaker that gets more than 80 percent of its revenue abroad,
rose 0.7 percent from the closing share price in Tokyo. Those of
 Canon Inc. (7751) , the world’s largest camera-maker, gained 0.4
percent. ADRs of  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , the world’s biggest mining
company, fell 0.3 percent after metal prices slipped.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
September closed at 8,670 in Chicago yesterday, up from 8,620 in
 Osaka , Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 8,680 in Osaka,
at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on Australia’s S&P/ASX 200
Index were little changed today. New Zealand’s NZX 50 Index rose
0.1 percent in Wellington.  “Risk aversion came to a halt in the U.S. and European
markets yesterday,” said Ryuta Otsuka, a strategist at Toyo
Securities Co. in Tokyo. “Stocks are likely to be bought as
valuations and technical indicators indicate they have been
oversold,”  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index were little
changed today. In  New York , most stocks fell on the index after
Goldman Sachs Group Inc.’s decline in the last 15 minutes of
trading wiped out the day’s rally. The measure closed little
changed.  Improved Data  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index fell 14 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with an 11 percent drop by the  S&P
500  and an 18 percent loss by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks
in the Asian benchmark are valued at 11.85 times estimated
earnings on average, compared with 11.26 times for the S&P 500
and 9.30 times for the Stoxx 600.  The  Chicago  Fed national index, a weighted average of 85
economic indicators, improved to minus 0.06 in July from minus
0.38 a month earlier, a Federal Reserve Bank of Chicago gauge
showed yesterday. The three-month average increased to minus
0.29 from June’s minus 0.54. Readings less than zero indicate
“below-trend” growth in the national economy, and the gauge
has been negative for four straight months.  European stocks rebounded from a two-year low yesterday as
prospects for an end to the war in Libya boosted energy
companies. The benchmark Stoxx Europe 600 Index rose 0.8 percent
to 224.9 at the 4:30 p.m. close in London.  The London Metal Exchange Index of prices for six
industrial metals including copper and aluminum declined 1.2
percent yesterday.  To contact the reporters on this story:
